					<head>Halakhic notes</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070287" rend="visible">
						<summary>Abraham Del Vecchio's notes (Tiḳune ha-Ri"f) on Berakhot and Halakhot ḳeṭanot, with an index to Agadot ha-Talmud.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="tmr-Hebr">Hebrew, Aramaic</textLang>
						<msItem rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070287">
							<locus from="1r" to="14v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Tiḳune ha-Ri&quot;f </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">תקוני הרי&quot;ף</title>
							<note>
								<p>The notes cover on Berakhot and Halakhot ḳeṭanot.</p>
								<p>Berakhot breaks off on folio 13v in the earlier portions of chapter 6.</p>
								<p>Folio 1v gives the title as: 'Sefer ha-zikhronot'.</p>
								<p>The work quotes several authorities, including Isaac Alfasi, Rashi, Asher ben Yehiel and Solomon ben Adret.</p>
							</note>
							<author key="http://viaf.org/viaf/36626487">
								<persName xml:lang="en">Del Vecchio, Samuel </persName>
								<persName xml:lang="he">דלוקיו, שמואל</persName>
							</author>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="15r" to="271v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Mafteaḥ agadot ha-Talmud  </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">מפתח אגדות התלמוד</title>
							<note>
								<p>The agadot are arranged in the alphabetical order, according to the inital word. The order followed under each letter is that of the tractates of the Talmud. Agadot of the Yerushalmi are given after the Bavli.</p>
								<p>The quotations from the opening of the various pieces sometimes extend over several sentences. </p>
								<p>Defective at the beginning. </p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
